{
  "texts": [
    "An essential step in systems science is the ability to represent a system in a way that supports analytical efforts.",
    "The representation depends on the application field and the task of interest (Voinov et al., 2018).",
    "For example, a physical system such as the climate can be represented via equations governing atmosphere and ground dynamics, analyzed by a solver to identify trends (e.g., change in precipitation) and affected areas (Sreenath, 1993).",
    "In contrast, cognitive and social systems are often represented via soft systems methodology, with an emphasis on capturing the mindset of stakeholders, their values and expectations, and the barriers to efficient policy interventions (Hieronymi, 2013).",
    "A network with more (e.g., causal loop diagram) or less (e.g., rich picture) constraints is often used as representation, for at least two reasons."
  ]
}